This theorem states that for a complex function `f` that is continuous on a closed ball and differentiable in the open ball, where both balls are centered at `c` with radius `R`, and excluding a countable set `s` that does not contain a complex number `w`, the line integral of the function `f` multiplied by the inverse of `(z - w)`, around the circumference of the circle `C(c, R)`, is equal to `2œÄi` times `f(w)`. This theorem assumes `w` does not belong to the set `s`, while the main theorem associated with this auxiliary lemma relaxes this assumption.
